# Java File Standards
# Type: By file path
# Pattern: **/*.java

## When generating or editing any .java file

### Class structure order (always follow this order)
1. Package declaration
2. Imports (no wildcard imports)
3. Javadoc
4. Class/interface/record/enum declaration
5. Static constants
6. Instance fields (final first, then mutable)
7. Constructors
8. Static factory methods
9. Public methods
10. Package-private methods
11. Private methods
12. equals() / hashCode() (identity-based for entities, structural for value objects)
13. toString()

### Imports
- No wildcard imports (import java.util.*)
- Group: java/javax, org, com, project-internal — separated by blank lines
- Remove unused imports before finishing

### Naming conventions
- Classes: UpperCamelCase, noun or noun phrase
- Interfaces: UpperCamelCase, can start with a verb (Processable) or be noun (OrderRepository)
- Methods: lowerCamelCase, verb phrase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Records components: lowerCamelCase nouns
- Test classes: {SubjectClass}Test
- Test methods: methodName_stateUnderTest_expectedBehaviour

### Exception handling in Java files
- Catch the most specific exception first
- Never swallow exceptions with empty catch blocks
- Always log the exception (with stack trace at ERROR level) before re-throwing or wrapping
- Wrap checked exceptions in an appropriate unchecked exception with a message that includes context
- Never catch Throwable in application code (only allowed in framework-level infrastructure)

### Records and immutability
- Prefer records for DTOs, commands, events and value objects
- Use compact constructor in records for validation: throw IllegalArgumentException, never return null
- If a field in a regular class is conceptually immutable, declare it final

### Generics
- Always bound wildcards meaningfully: prefer <T extends Processable> over raw <T> where applicable
- Do not suppress unchecked cast warnings without a comment explaining why it is safe

### Logging in Java files
- Logger declaration: private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(ClassName.class)
- Log method entry at DEBUG for complex methods with parameters relevant to tracing
- Log significant state transitions at INFO
- Log recoverable failures at WARN with context
- Log unexpected failures at ERROR with the full exception
- Never construct log messages with string concatenation inside the log call; use parameterized form: log.info("Order {} created", orderId)
